## Generalization

The central question in applied ML:

> Does the model work on new data, or did it only memorize the training data?

Key vocabulary:

- **Overfitting:** model memorizes training data too closely.
- **Underfitting:** model is too simple to capture useful patterns.
- **Generalization:** model performs well on unseen data.

# Model Assessment {background-color="#F2EEE8"}

## Overfitting and underfitting

| Model behavior | Training performance | Test performance |
|----------------|---------------------:|-----------------:|
| Underfit       |                 Poor |             Poor |
| Good fit       |                 Good |             Good |
| Overfit        |            Excellent |             Poor |

Marketing example: a churn model that memorizes last semester’s customer quirks may fail on this semester’s customers.

## What makes a model “good”?

It depends on the decision.

::::: columns
::: {.column width="50%"}
### Regression metrics

- RMSE
- MAE
- R-squared
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
### Classification metrics

- Accuracy
- Sensitivity / recall
- Specificity
- Precision
- ROC AUC
:::
:::::

::: fragment
A model can be accurate and still useless for marketing.
:::

## Accuracy can mislead

Suppose only 5% of customers churn.

A model that predicts **“no churn” for everyone** is 95% accurate.

But it identifies exactly **zero** customers for retention action.

::: callout-important
The best model is not always the most accurate model. It is the one that improves the marketing decision.
:::

