# Tidymodels Coding Example {background-color="#F2EEE8"}

## Workflow

```{mermaid}
%%| echo: false

flowchart TB
  A[customer_data] --> B[initial_split]
  B --> C[training data]
  B --> D[testing data]
  C --> E[fit model]
  E --> F[predict on test data]
  F --> G[evaluate performance]
```

This code is a preview. We will build the full workflow step by step across the course.

## Mini example: first tidymodels taste

```{r}
#| eval: false
#install.packages("tidymodels")
library(tidymodels)

set.seed(123)

# Imagine customer_data contains sales, ad_spend, price, and promotion
sales_split <- initial_split(customer_data, prop = 0.80)
sales_train <- training(sales_split)
sales_test <- testing(sales_split)

lm_spec <- linear_reg() |>
  set_engine("lm")

lm_fit <- lm_spec |>
  fit(sales ~ ad_spend + price + promotion, data = sales_train)

sales_pred <- predict(lm_fit, sales_test)
```

## Responsible ML starts now

Marketing ML can be powerful, but it raises real questions:

- Are we using customer data transparently?
- Could our model treat groups unfairly?
- Are we predicting sensitive traits indirectly?
- Can we explain decisions to stakeholders?
- Does personalization cross a trust boundary?

::: callout-question
Discussion: Just because we can predict something about customers, should we use it?
:::

